It is a fixed law of nature that in any kind of commissariat bread⁰ a third part is added in the making to the weight of the grain, just as that the best whcat is that which absorbs three quarts of water into the peck of grain kneaded. Some kinds of grain used by themselves give their full weight, for instance a peck of Balearic wheat produces 35 pounds of bread, but some only do so when blended—for example, Cyprian wheat and Alexandrian, which used by thern- selves do not go beyond 20 pounds a peck. Cyprus wheat is of a dusky colour and makes black bread, and consequently the white Alexandrian is mixed with it, and that gives 25 pounds of bread to the peck. The wheat of the Thebaid in Egypt makes a pound more.
